<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1879-05-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1879-05-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="107" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d107">
                    <head>No. 91.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Seward</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Osborn</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-05-29"><hi rend="italic">May</hi> 29,
                            1879</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 63.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                        dispatch of the 19th ultimo (92), in which you send me a copy and a
                        translation of the manifests of the Government of Chili, in justification of
                        its war with Peru.</p>
                    <p>Whatever may have been the causes leading to this war, its commencement and
                        continuance cannot but be regretted by the United States; and it is hardly
                        necessary to add that the announcement of an early peace between the two
                        governments, as also with Bolivia, would be news most welcome to the
                        Government of the United States.</p>
                    <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>F. W. SEWARD,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting
                            Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>